This project implements a Part-of-Speech tagger from first principles using a Hidden Markov Model with Viterbi decoding, trained and evaluated on the NLTK Penn Treebank corpus with the Universal Tagset. 
Transition and emission probabilities are estimated via frequency counts with Laplace smoothing, and an unknown-word handling extension using tag-prior probabilities improves validation accuracy from 90.09% to 90.46%. 
Quantitative and qualitative analysis identify specific sentences where unknown-word handling corrects tagging errors made by the baseline model. 
Built entirely in Python without pre-built tagging libraries, the project demonstrates core NLP sequence-modeling techniques, including dynamic programming-based decoding and probabilistic smoothing.

